caption: Have been here only once while visiting D.C. The ambience is nice and in normal times the place can seat 50-70 people. We tried spicy tuna rolls, salmon + scallion rolls and Thai fried rice. Nooshi is known for its legendary happy hour. The drinks are plenty, the bartenders have a good pour, and best of all, it's cheap! It can get pretty busy but the place has a great vibe, service is great, and there's outdoor sidewalk seating for warmer days. Unfortunately, a lot of the outdoor tables are rickety and, annoyingly, do not balance.  As mentioned, drinks are great-- but the food is also pretty decent as well. It always comes out piping hot and the ingredients taste fresh. A favorite of mine is the tom kha soup-- it's amazing with chicken or shrimp. While the food here isn't the most "authentic" or even the best Asian/Thai food you can find in the District, it's more than good enough.  Things I Like: Tom Kha Soup - This soup is delicious-- it's difficult for any Thai restaurant to mess up considering it's a staple of Thai cuisine. Get it with shrimp! Thai Fried Rice - This goes really well with the chicken. Definitely get a side of hot sauce  Things I Dislike: Honey Peanut Chicken - The egg noodles are great, but this dish is far too sweet; the honey is overbearing on the peanut flavor and it's difficult to have more than a few bites.

I have been to Nooshi a few times for lunch and this review is for the Lunch menu. The restaurant may have a nondescript entrance but is it is quite hip inside. They have quite a few tables for dining but they do get filled up fast during busy lunch hours.  I a fan of their Vietnamese Spring Rolls, Sichuan Dragon Dumpling for appetizers and Spicy Seafood Ramen for the main course. The main dish is generous and does fill me up. The broth is a tad bit too spicy for me, but then I have low tolerance to spicy food. The flavors and taste of the broth is good tho!  Sushi here is quite fresh and there is a good variety of sushi options to choose from.  Service is prompt and efficient which makes the dining experience that much better!

I ordered the Drunken Noodle and asked to have it made extra spicy. I could barely taste the spice. The noodles were clumped up at the bottom, and didn't look like they had been cooked in the sauce, and seemed like the sauce was merely poured over it. The noodles also broke very easily. When I speared one noodle with my fork, it would just break wherever my fork went through like day old noodle does (I don't know if the noodles were day old, but they sure seemed like it). Like I said, the noodles were clumped up at the bottom, so it was impossible to eat one or two noodles, I had to just get a giant clump of noodle and eat that or else no noodle at all (because the noodles broke if I tried to de-clump). The two stars are for generally good tasting veggies/meat and decent portion size.
